The Richter shown here was probably early aviator Joseph P. Richter. His name was German (&quot;Richter&quot; means judge), but he was an American:

&quot;Reading, Pa. -- Aeroplane mail service was authorized for Reading, Pa., for September 10, 1912. The route was . . . to have started from the Reading Fairgrounds. The late arrival of the machine of aviator Joseph Richter prevented the service from being carried out.&quot;
--Mekeel's Weekly Stamp News, Volume 27.

&quot;In 1923... The first refueling in mid-air (with hose) of one airplane by another is made by a De Havilland D.H.4-b from another one over San Diego, California. The planes are flown by Capt. L. H. Smith and Lt. J. P. Richter.&quot;
--Internet.
